  </Hero>

  {/* ───────── Why manual publishing fails — lead + contrast panel ───────── */}
  <section class="pa-section pa-section--framing" aria-labelledby="framing-heading">
    <div class="container-data pa-section__inner">
      <h2 id="framing-heading" class="pa-section__heading">Why manual publishing fails.</h2>
      <p class="pa-section__lead pa-framing__lead">
        Publishing automation isn't about speed — it's about risk. Manual publishing looks functional while quietly skipping every quality control; the pipeline runs them deterministically, on every commit, and fails defects loudly at the moment they're cheapest to fix.
      </p>

      <div class="pa-contrast">
        <div class="pa-contrast__card pa-contrast__card--bad">
          <div class="pa-contrast__head">
            <p class="pa-contrast__eyebrow">Manual</p>
            <p class="pa-contrast__sub">from a laptop</p>
          </div>
          <p class="pa-contrast__method">A writer runs DITA-OT by hand, locally.</p>
          <ul class="pa-contrast__list">
            <li>Different Java, plugins, and results per machine</li>
            <li>Broken links and invalid XML found after the build</li>
            <li>PDF emailed to reviewers; feedback in a Word doc</li>
            <li>No JSONL build — "that's an AI team problem"</li>
          </ul>
          <p class="pa-contrast__out">
            <span class="pa-contrast__mark pa-contrast__mark--x" aria-hidden="true">&#10005;</span>
            Every step is a quality control that isn't being run.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="pa-contrast__card pa-contrast__card--good">
          <div class="pa-contrast__head">
            <p class="pa-contrast__eyebrow">Automated</p>
            <p class="pa-contrast__sub">extense.ci</p>
          </div>
          <p class="pa-contrast__method">Every commit triggers a containerized pipeline.</p>
          <ul class="pa-contrast__list">
            <li>One image, one toolchain, identical output</li>
            <li>Gates block bad XML, links, and metadata before merge</li>
            <li>Reviewers get a staging URL; feedback is a PR comment</li>
            <li>HTML5, PDF, and chatbot-ready JSONL in parallel</li>
          </ul>
          <p class="pa-contrast__out">
            <span class="pa-contrast__mark pa-contrast__mark--check" aria-hidden="true">&#10003;</span>
            Defects fail at the cheapest moment to fix them.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  {/* ───────── Before -> after stat band ───────── */}
  <section class="pa-section pa-stats" aria-labelledby="stats-heading">
    <div class="container-data pa-section__inner">
      <h2 id="stats-heading" class="pa-section__visually-hidden">Publishing automation by the numbers.</h2>
      <ul class="pa-stats__grid">
        {stats.map((s, i) => (
          <li class="pa-stat" style={`--d: ${i * 100}ms`}>
            <span class="pa-stat__value">{s.value}</span>
            <span class="pa-stat__label">{s.label}</span>
            <span class="pa-stat__sub">{s.sub}</span>
          </li>
        ))}
      </ul>
    </div>
  </section>

  {/* ───────── The eight-stage pipeline (validation folded in) ───────── */}
  <section class="pa-section pa-section--pipeline" aria-labelledby="pipeline-heading">
    <div class="container-data pa-section__inner">
      <h2 id="pipeline-heading" class="pa-section__heading">The eight-stage pipeline.</h2>
      <p class="pa-section__lead">
        Eight stages from commit to production. Each names the action that runs and the result it produces. The validation gates that surface defects are integrated into the stages, not staged separately — defects fail at the moment they're cheapest to fix.
      </p>

      <ol class="pa-pipeline">
        {pipelineStages.map((s) => (
          <li class="pa-stage">
            <span class="pa-stage__num" aria-hidden="true">{s.number}</span>
            <p class="pa-stage__name">{s.name}</p>
            <div class="pa-stage__col pa-stage__col--runs">
              <p class="pa-stage__col-label">What runs</p>
              <p class="pa-stage__col-body">{s.runs}</p>
            </div>
            <div class="pa-stage__col pa-stage__col--result">
              <p class="pa-stage__col-label">Result</p>
              <p class="pa-stage__col-body">{s.result}</p>
            </div>
          </li>
        ))}
      </ol>
    </div>
  </section>

  {/* ───────── Containerization ───────── */}
  <section class="pa-section pa-section--container" aria-labelledby="container-heading">
    <div class="container-data pa-section__inner">
      <h2 id="container-heading" class="pa-section__heading">Containerization is the single largest change.</h2>
      <p class="pa-section__lead">
        DITA-OT depends on Java, Saxon, Apache FOP, and a stack of plugins — each with version-specific behavior. When Writer A runs DITA-OT 4.1 with Java 17 and Writer B runs DITA-OT 3.7 with Java 11, the same source produces different output. In regulated industries — defense, life sciences, financial services — that is a compliance failure, not a stylistic one.
      </p>
      <div class="pa-split">
        <div class="pa-split__main">
          <p class="pa-section__body">
            A Docker image locks the entire toolchain into a single, versioned artifact: DITA-OT version, Java version, custom plugins, fonts, and configuration. The pipeline pulls the image and runs the build. Every build. Every environment. Identical output. The "it works on my machine" failure mode disappears because the machine is now the image.
          </p>

          <p class="pa-stack__eyebrow">What's in the image</p>
          <hr class="pa-rule" />
          <dl class="pa-stack">
            {containerLayers.map((row) => (
              <div class="pa-stack__row">
                <dt class="pa-stack__label">{row.label}</dt>
                <dd class="pa-stack__value">{row.value}</dd>
              </div>
            ))}
          </dl>
          <hr class="pa-rule" />

          <p class="pa-section__body">
            Once the image is built and pushed to a container registry, every CI job uses the same image. GitHub Actions, Azure DevOps, Jenkins, and GitLab CI all support container-based jobs natively — the CI platform pulls the image, mounts the source, and runs the build.
          </p>
        </div>
        <aside class="pa-split__aside">
          <p class="pa-code__eyebrow">Dockerfile</p>
          <pre class="pa-code"><code>{dockerfile}</code></pre>
          <p class="pa-code__eyebrow">Pipeline usage</p>
          <pre class="pa-code"><code>{dockerRun}</code></pre>
        </aside>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  {/* ───────── Output formats ───────── */}
  <section class="pa-section pa-section--formats" aria-labelledby="formats-heading">
    <div class="container-data pa-section__inner">
      <h2 id="formats-heading" class="pa-section__heading">Output formats from a single source.</h2>
      <p class="pa-section__lead">
        Four production-grade output formats generated in parallel from one DITA bookmap. JSONL is treated as a first-class output, not a separate "AI pipeline" — it ships from the same commit, validated by the same gates.
      </p>

      <div class="pa-split">
        <ol class="pa-formats pa-split__main">
        {outputFormats.map((f, i) => (
          <li class="pa-format">
            <span class="pa-format__num" aria-hidden="true">{String(i + 1).padStart(2, "0")}</span>
            <div class="pa-format__body">
              <h3 class="pa-format__name">{f.name}</h3>
              <p class="pa-format__desc">{f.description}</p>
              <p class="pa-format__build">
                <span class="pa-format__build-tag">Typical build:</span> {f.build}
              </p>
            </div>
          </li>
        ))}
        </ol>
        <aside class="pa-split__aside">
          <p class="pa-code__eyebrow">Build configuration</p>
          <pre class="pa-code"><code>{gradle}</code></pre>
        </aside>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  {/* ───────── CI/CD platforms ───────── */}
  <section class="pa-section pa-section--platforms" aria-labelledby="platforms-heading">
    <div class="container-data pa-section__inner">
      <h2 id="platforms-heading" class="pa-section__heading">CI/CD platforms.</h2>
      <p class="pa-section__lead">
        The pipeline is platform-portable because containerization decouples the build from the CI runner. Below: four supported platforms and the criteria for choosing each. The GitHub Actions configuration is included as a worked example — the Azure DevOps, Jenkins, and GitLab equivalents are structurally similar.
      </p>

      <div class="pa-split">
        <ol class="pa-platforms pa-split__main">
        {platforms.map((p, i) => (
          <li class="pa-platform">
            <span class="pa-platform__num" aria-hidden="true">{String(i + 1).padStart(2, "0")}</span>
            <div class="pa-platform__body">
              <h3 class="pa-platform__name">{p.name}</h3>
              <p class="pa-platform__desc">{p.body}</p>
            </div>
          </li>
        ))}
        </ol>
        <aside class="pa-split__aside">
          <p class="pa-code__eyebrow">GitHub Actions — worked example</p>
          <pre class="pa-code"><code>{githubActionsYml}</code></pre>
        </aside>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  {/* ───────── Custom DITA-OT plugins ───────── */}
  <section class="pa-section pa-section--plugins" aria-labelledby="plugins-heading">
    <div class="container-data pa-section__inner">
      <h2 id="plugins-heading" class="pa-section__heading">Custom DITA-OT plugins.</h2>
      <p class="pa-section__lead">
        Off-the-shelf DITA-OT output is a starting point. Production documentation needs custom branding, navigation, and export formats — and those customizations belong in versioned plugins, not in someone's local install.
      </p>

      <ol class="pa-plugins">
        {plugins.map((p, i) => (
          <li class="pa-plugin">
            <span class="pa-plugin__num" aria-hidden="true">{String(i + 1).padStart(2, "0")}</span>
            <div class="pa-plugin__body">
              <h3 class="pa-plugin__name">{p.name}</h3>
              <p class="pa-plugin__desc">{p.body}</p>
            </div>
          </li>
        ))}
      </ol>

      <p class="pa-section__body pa-section__body--principle">
        Every custom plugin is a versioned, testable artifact in the Git repository — not a one-off customization buried in someone's local DITA-OT installation. We build plugins with automated tests, document the configuration parameters, and train the client team to maintain them. When DITA-OT releases a new version, we validate plugin compatibility and update where needed.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <CTAModule
    audience="general"
    accentLine
    body="Send your current build process — Jenkinsfile, GitHub Actions workflow, or a description of the manual steps — and we'll return a gap analysis with a recommended automation roadmap within two business days. No obligation to proceed."
  />
</BaseLayout>

